hire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Deross","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Salvatore.","Americanized form of Dutch   De Roos  .","Americanized form of Italian   De Rossi   or   Di Russo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"De Roos","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Dirk, Frans, Antoon, Derk.","Dutch: from <i>roos</i> ‘rose’ with the addition of the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’, probably a topographic or habitational name referring to a house distinguished by the sign of a rose, or possibly a nickname for a man with a rosy complexion. Compare   De Rose  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":8,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars